Introduction¶

The Bay Area's bikeshare program is called Ford GoBike was introduced in 2013, and have featured thousands of bikes and across 70 stations around San Francisco. The Ford GoBike uses a fleet of strong, durable bikes that are secured into a system of docking stations spread out over the city. This document explores individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area. This dataset is the ford Bikeshare for the month of Feburary 2019.

Source: Ford GoBike System Data

NOTE: I wanted to get the entire dataset for the entire year of forebike but the link is broken Systems Data Page

Quality issues¶

  1. Missing values in member_gender, member_birth_year, end_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_id and end_station_name
  2. Start_time, and end_time should be datatime datatype
  3. bike_share_for_all_trip, User_type and member_gender should be catergory datatype
  4. The member_birth_year, start_station_id and end_station_id is having a decimal value and has a wrong data type

Tidiness issues¶

There are no tidiness issues:\ Every column is a variable,\ Every row is an observation,\ Every cell is a single value and every rows and columns forms a table

  1. But I want to create a feature age and see if we can further turn it to a categorical feature of young and old or more
  2. Distance covered for each member
  3. Create a column for Start month, end month, day of the week, minutes and hour of trip duration

Tidness¶

Issue 1¶

Define¶

There is need for an age feature, it hard to do a mental calculation looking at the birth years of the users, hence a need for age feature

Code¶

In [23]:
# since the data only provides us with the birth year of each memeber
# I will just substract the birth year from the current year for which this analysis is doen
# and for reproducibility I won't just use the current year but a function that can input current year
# regardless of what year the code is ran, so the ages are updated, 
# so I use the datetime.now to get the extact date
from datetime import datetime as dt

def age(born):
    today = dt.now().year
    return today -born
In [24]:

Issue 2¶

Define¶

The lattitude and longitude are great features but at and instance it can't tell tell the distance covered expecct one starts does a calculation, here I would use the longitude and latitude to get the distance covered for each member

  • Reference: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/40452759/pandas-latitude-longitude-to-distance-between-successive-rows https://stackoverflow.com/questions/19412462/getting-distance-between-two-points-based-on-latitude-longitude

Code¶

In [32]:
# Will be using the math radians, sin, cos, sqrt and atan2
from math import radians, sin, cos, sqrt, atan2

def distance(start, end):
    
# The approximate earth radius, 6371 is in kilometers 
    lat1, long1 = start
    lat2, long2 = end
    radius = 6371

    dlat = radians(lat2 - lat1)
    dlong = radians(long2 - long1)
    
    a = (sin(dlat / 2) * sin(dlat / 2) + cos(radians(lat1)) * cos(radians(lat2)) * sin(dlong / 2) * sin(dlong / 2))
    c = 2 * atan2(sqrt(a), sqrt(1 - a))
    distance = radius * c

    # Round up the values to two decimal places
    return round(distance, 2)
In [33]:
bike_clean['distance_km'] = bike_clean.apply(lambda x: distance((x['start_station_latitude'], x['start_station_longitude']), 
                                                            (x['end_station_latitude'], x['end_station_longitude'])), 
                                         axis=1)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The Ford GoBike data after cleaning and feature engineering have 23 features, which includes 3 categorical data, 2 datetime data, 5 floating point data, 9 intergers and 4 strings. The dataset has 174952 rows.

The columns original feature:

  • duration_sec
  • start_time
  • end_time
  • start_station_id
  • start_station_name
  • start_station_latitude
  • start_station_longitude
  • end_station_id
  • end_station_name
  • end_station_latitude
  • end_station_longitude
  • bike_id
  • user_type
  • member_birth_year
  • member_gender
  • bike_share_for_all_trip

The feature engineered columns:

  • member_age
  • distance_km
  • start_time_weekday
  • start_time_hour
  • end_time_hour
  • duration_minutes

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of interest would inlcudes:

  • Getting insight to making better business decisons on target auidence and how the different subscribes, age and member influences the user of ford Gobike in San Francisco.
  • Also it would be interesting to what weekday has the highest duration of user in minutes and by members, this would influnce the Fold Gobike on making readily available large amounts of bike during any of those week days

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The Main features that would be supporting my investigation would include

  • starting hour
  • distance_km
  • duration_minutes
  • user_type
  • start_time_weekday
  • member_gender and member_age

Nothing appears to be unusual for a bike sharing program in a san Francisco. According to the statistics so far, the system's main user base consists of individuals in the typical working age range who utilize the bikes for their everyday journeys.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Subscription use is far higher than consumer usage. Customers and subscribers have quite different riding habits and patterns. Most trips on work days (Mon-Fri) and especially during rush hours (when going to work in the morning and getting off work in the afternoon/evening) were made by subscribers because they use the bike sharing system for commuting, whereas customers typically ride for fun in the afternoon or early evening on weekends but there is a strange twist showing that users on weekends (Saturday and Sunday) trend to spend longer time on bike rides. The average ride length is somewhat greater for subscriber users than for consumer users.\ Ages between 25 and 40 are the most active users, while spending longer minutes on rides this age bracket are most like to start there ride within the hours of 3pm and 8pm

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

It was intresting see that most users of the Ford Bike used it for all trips and this was recorded most on Thursdays

The link between the various variables plotted is seen collectively and information is displayed simultaneously, strengthening some of the patterns identified in the preceding bivariate investigation as well as in the univariate research. Subscribers' efficient/short periods of consumption are consistent with their high concentration during Monday through Friday rush hours, showing that the use is mostly for commuting to work. Customers clearly utilize the bike sharing system considerably differently than subscribers, frequently on weekends and in the afternoons, perhaps for leisure or city tours, as seen by the more flexible and loose pattern of their usage.
